Title: Alice's Adventures in Wonderland
Credit: Written by
Author: Lewis Carroll
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/15/2025
Notes: Period live-action fantasy with practical creature costumes and gentle optical effects; warm summer English countryside giving way to theatrical Wonderland. ALICE is a curious girl of about seven, fair hair half-loose with a ribbon, blue dress, white apron, striped stockings. WHITE RABBIT: white fur, pink eyes, waistcoat, pocket-watch. CHESHIRE CAT: striped cat with an enduring grin. MAD HATTER: tall hat, eccentric tea-stained clothes. MARCH HARE: hare in mismatched tea-party attire. DORMOUSE: small sleepy dormouse. KING OF HEARTS and QUEEN OF HEARTS: playing-card royalty. KNAVE OF HEARTS: cardboard knave. SISTER: older girl in simple summer dress.

===

EXT. RIVERBANK - DAY

A hot summer afternoon. ALICE, about seven, fair hair half-tamed by a ribbon, blue dress and white apron, sits beside her SISTER on the grassy bank. Sister reads a dense book without pictures. Alice peeps at the pages, restless, sleepy, and bored.

NARRATOR
Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting by her sister on the bank, and of having nothing to do.

Alice glances once more at the book, then lies back among the daisies.

ALICE
(to herself)
And what is the use of a book without pictures or conversations?

She considers making a daisy-chain, too drowsy to rise—when a WHITE RABBIT with pink eyes, wearing a waistcoat, runs close by.

WHITE RABBIT
Oh dear! Oh dear! I shall be late!

The Rabbit takes a watch from its waistcoat-pocket, looks at it, and hurries on. Alice starts to her feet, burning with curiosity, and runs across the field after it.

EXT. HEDGE AND RABBIT-HOLE - DAY

Just in time, Alice sees the White Rabbit pop down a large rabbit-hole under the hedge. In another moment she goes down after it, never once considering how she is to get out again.

INT. RABBIT-HOLE TUNNEL - CONTINUOUS

The hole runs on like a tunnel, then dips suddenly. Alice falls down a very deep well—slowly enough to look about her.

Cupboards and book-shelves line the sides; maps and pictures hang upon pegs. As she passes, she takes down a jar labelled ORANGE MARMALADE—empty. She manages to put it into a cupboard as she falls.

ALICE
Well! After such a fall as this, I shall think nothing of tumbling down stairs! How brave they'll all think me at home!

Down, down, down.

ALICE
I wonder how many miles I've fallen by this time? I must be getting somewhere near the centre of the earth. Four thousand miles down, I think—yes, that's about the right distance—but then I wonder what Latitude or Longitude I've got to?

She tries a little curtsey in mid-air and nearly turns over.

ALICE
Please, Ma'am, is this New Zealand or Australia? No, it'll never do to ask: perhaps I shall see it written up somewhere.

Down, down, down. She grows dreamy.

ALICE
Dinah'll miss me very much to-night, I should think! I hope they'll remember her saucer of milk at tea-time. Dinah my dear! I wish you were down here with me! Do cats eat bats? Do cats eat bats? Do bats eat cats?

THUMP. THUMP. She lands on a heap of sticks and dry leaves. The fall is over.

INT. LONG PASSAGE AND HALL - DAY

Alice is not hurt. She jumps up. Overhead is dark; before her, another long passage. The White Rabbit is still in sight, hurrying away.

WHITE RABBIT
Oh my ears and whiskers, how late it's getting!

Alice races after him, turns the corner—and the Rabbit is gone. She stands in a long, low hall lit by a row of lamps hanging from the roof. Doors all round; all locked. She tries every one, then walks sadly down the middle.

A little three-legged table of solid glass stands nearby. On it: a tiny golden key. Alice tries the key on the doors—locks too large, or key too small. On a second round she finds a low curtain and, behind it, a little door about fifteen inches high. The golden key fits.

She opens the door onto a small passage no larger than a rat-hole, and beyond it the loveliest garden—bright flowers, cool fountains. She longs to enter but cannot get even her head through.

ALICE
And even if my head would go through, it would be of very little use without my shoulders. Oh, how I wish I could shut up like a telescope!

She goes back to the table. This time a little bottle stands on it, a paper label round its neck:

DRINK ME

ALICE
No, I'll look first, and see whether it's marked "poison" or not.

It is not marked poison. She tastes—cherry-tart, custard, pineapple, roast turkey, toffee, and hot buttered toast—and finishes it off.

ALICE
What a curious feeling! I must be shutting up like a telescope.

She shrinks to ten inches high. Her face brightens—she is the right size for the garden door. She waits; she shrinks no further.

ALICE
For it might end, you know, in my going out altogether, like a candle.

She runs to the door—and has forgotten the golden key. Back at the table she cannot reach it; the glass is plain, the legs too slippery. Exhausted, she sits down and cries.

ALICE
Come, there's no use in crying like that! I advise you to leave off this minute!

Her eye falls on a little glass box under the table. Inside: a very small cake with EAT ME marked in currants.

ALICE
Well, I'll eat it, and if it makes me grow larger, I can reach the key; and if it makes me grow smaller, I can creep under the door; so either way I'll get into the garden, and I don't care which happens!

She eats a little bit, hand on her head.

ALICE
Which way? Which way?

She remains the same size—surprised, still hopeful—holding the rest of the cake as the hall seems to wait with her.

EXT. WOODS PATH - DAY

Later in Wonderland. Alice, now a sensible walking height again, comes upon a CHESHIRE CAT—striped, perched in a tree, grinning from ear to ear.

ALICE
Cheshire Puss... would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?

CHESHIRE CAT
That depends a good deal on where you want to get to.

ALICE
I don't much care where—

CHESHIRE CAT
Then it doesn't matter which way you go.

ALICE
—so long as I get somewhere.

CHESHIRE CAT
Oh, you're sure to do that, if you only walk long enough.

ALICE
What sort of people live about here?

CHESHIRE CAT
(waving right paw)
In that direction lives a Hatter:
(waving other paw)
and in that direction lives a March Hare. Visit either you like: they're both mad.

ALICE
But I don't want to go among mad people.

CHESHIRE CAT
Oh, you can't help that. We're all mad here. I'm mad. You're mad.

ALICE
How do you know I'm mad?

CHESHIRE CAT
You must be, or you wouldn't have come here.

ALICE
And how do you know that you're mad?

CHESHIRE CAT
To begin with, a dog's not mad. You grant that?

ALICE
I suppose so.

CHESHIRE CAT
Well, then: a dog growls when it's angry, and wags its tail when it's pleased. Now I growl when I'm pleased, and wag my tail when I'm angry. Therefore I'm mad.

ALICE
I call it purring, not growling.

CHESHIRE CAT
Call it what you like. Do you play croquet with the Queen to-day?

ALICE
I should like it very much, but I haven't been invited yet.

CHESHIRE CAT
You'll see me there.

The Cat vanishes. Alice stares at the empty branch. The Cat reappears.

CHESHIRE CAT
By-the-bye, what became of the baby? I'd nearly forgotten to ask.

ALICE
It turned into a pig.

CHESHIRE CAT
I thought it would.

It vanishes again. Alice waits, then walks on toward the March Hare.

ALICE
(to herself)
I've seen hatters before; the March Hare will be much the most interesting, and perhaps as this is May it won't be raving mad—at least not so mad as it was in March.

The Cat appears once more on a branch.

CHESHIRE CAT
Did you say pig, or fig?

ALICE
I said pig, and I wish you wouldn't keep appearing and vanishing so suddenly: you make one quite giddy.

CHESHIRE CAT
All right.

This time it vanishes slowly—from the end of the tail to the grin, which remains some time after the rest has gone.

ALICE
(to herself)
Well! I've often seen a cat without a grin; but a grin without a cat! It's the most curious thing I ever saw in my life!

EXT. MARCH HARE'S HOUSE - DAY

The house has chimneys shaped like ears and a roof thatched with fur. Alice nibbles a bit of mushroom from her pocket, settles at about two feet high, and approaches timidly.

ALICE
(to herself)
Suppose it should be raving mad after all! I almost wish I'd gone to see the Hatter instead!

EXT. TEA TABLE UNDER TREE - DAY

A long table set for many under a tree. The MARCH HARE and the MAD HATTER take tea; a DORMOUSE sits between them, fast asleep, used as a cushion as they rest elbows on it and talk over its head.

They are crowded at one corner. Alice approaches.

MARCH HARE AND MAD HATTER
No room! No room!

ALICE
There's plenty of room!

She sits in a large arm-chair at one end.

MARCH HARE
(encouraging)
Have some wine.

Alice looks; there is nothing but tea.

ALICE
I don't see any wine.

MARCH HARE
There isn't any.

ALICE
Then it wasn't very civil of you to offer it.

MARCH HARE
It wasn't very civil of you to sit down without being invited.

ALICE
I didn't know it was your table; it's laid for a great many more than three.

MAD HATTER
(looking at her with curiosity)
Your hair wants cutting.

ALICE
You should learn not to make personal remarks; it's very rude.

The Hatter opens his eyes very wide.

MAD HATTER
Why is a raven like a writing-desk?

ALICE
(to herself, pleased)
Come, we shall have some fun now! I'm glad they've begun asking riddles.
(aloud)
I believe I can guess that.

MARCH HARE
Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it?

ALICE
Exactly so.

MARCH HARE
Then you should say what you mean.

ALICE
I do; at least—at least I mean what I say—that's the same thing, you know.

MAD HATTER
Not the same thing a bit! You might just as well say that "I see what I eat" is the same thing as "I eat what I see"!

MARCH HARE
You might just as well say that "I like what I get" is the same thing as "I get what I like"!

DORMOUSE
(asleep, murmuring)
You might just as well say that "I breathe when I sleep" is the same thing as "I sleep when I breathe"!

MAD HATTER
It is the same thing with you.

Silence. Alice thinks hard about ravens and writing-desks. The Hatter takes out a watch, shakes it, holds it to his ear.

MAD HATTER
What day of the month is it?

ALICE
The fourth.

MAD HATTER
(sighs)
Two days wrong! I told you butter wouldn't suit the works!

MARCH HARE
It was the best butter.

MAD HATTER
Yes, but some crumbs must have got in as well; you shouldn't have put it in with the bread-knife.

The March Hare dips the watch into his tea, looks gloomily at it.

MARCH HARE
It was the best butter, you know.

ALICE
What a funny watch! It tells the day of the month, and doesn't tell what o'clock it is!

MAD HATTER
Why should it? Does your watch tell you what year it is?

ALICE
Of course not; but that's because it stays the same year for such a long time together.

MAD HATTER
Which is just the case with mine.

ALICE
I don't quite understand you.

MAD HATTER
The Dormouse is asleep again.

He pours a little hot tea upon its nose. The Dormouse shakes its head without opening its eyes.

DORMOUSE
Of course, of course; just what I was going to remark myself.

MAD HATTER
Have you guessed the riddle yet?

Alice looks from one mad face to the other; the endless tea things glitter; the Dormouse snores. She will not stay forever among the cups.

INT. COURT OF HEARTS - DAY

A great hall of cards. The KING OF HEARTS and QUEEN OF HEARTS preside. The KNAVE OF HEARTS stands prisoner. A jury of creatures scribbles on slates. The WHITE RABBIT, spectacles ready, bustles with papers. On the table: a dish of tarts. Alice stands among the crowd—already growing larger by the minute, less and less afraid.

KING OF HEARTS
It's the oldest rule in the book.

ALICE
Then it ought to be Number One.

The King turns pale and shuts his note-book hastily.

KING OF HEARTS
(to the jury, trembling)
Consider your verdict.

WHITE RABBIT
(jumping up)
There's more evidence to come yet, please your Majesty; this paper has just been picked up.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
What's in it?

WHITE RABBIT
I haven't opened it yet, but it seems to be a letter, written by the prisoner to—to somebody.

KING OF HEARTS
It must have been that, unless it was written to nobody, which isn't usual, you know.

A JURYMAN
Who is it directed to?

WHITE RABBIT
It isn't directed at all; in fact, there's nothing written on the outside.
(unfolds it)
It isn't a letter, after all: it's a set of verses.

ANOTHER JURYMAN
Are they in the prisoner's handwriting?

WHITE RABBIT
No, they're not, and that's the queerest thing about it.

KING OF HEARTS
He must have imitated somebody else's hand.

KNAVE OF HEARTS
Please your Majesty, I didn't write it, and they can't prove I did: there's no name signed at the end.

KING OF HEARTS
If you didn't sign it, that only makes the matter worse. You must have meant some mischief, or else you'd have signed your name like an honest man.

A general clapping of hands.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
That proves his guilt.

ALICE
It proves nothing of the sort! Why, you don't even know what they're about!

KING OF HEARTS
Read them.

The White Rabbit puts on his spectacles.

WHITE RABBIT
Where shall I begin, please your Majesty?

KING OF HEARTS
Begin at the beginning, and go on till you come to the end: then stop.

WHITE RABBIT
(reading)
They told me you had been to her,
And mentioned me to him:
She gave me a good character,
But said I could not swim.

He sent them word I had not gone
(We know it to be true):
If she should push the matter on,
What would become of you?

I gave her one, they gave him two,
You gave us three or more;
They all returned from him to you,
Though they were mine before.

If I or she should chance to be
Involved in this affair,
He trusts to you to set them free,
Exactly as we were.

My notion was that you had been
(Before she had this fit)
An obstacle that came between
Him, and ourselves, and it.

Don't let him know she liked them best,
For this must ever be
A secret, kept from all the rest,
Between yourself and me.

KING OF HEARTS
(rubbing his hands)
That's the most important piece of evidence we've heard yet; so now let the jury—

ALICE
(interrupting; she has grown so large she is not a bit afraid)
If any one of them can explain it, I'll give him sixpence. I don't believe there's an atom of meaning in it.

The jury write on their slates: SHE doesn't believe there's an atom of meaning in it.

KING OF HEARTS
If there's no meaning in it, that saves a world of trouble, you know, as we needn't try to find any. And yet I don't know—
(spreading the verses, one eye on them)
I seem to see some meaning in them, after all. "—said I could not swim—" you can't swim, can you?

He turns to the Knave. The Knave, entirely of cardboard, shakes his head sadly.

KNAVE OF HEARTS
Do I look like it?

KING OF HEARTS
All right, so far.
(muttering)
"We know it to be true—" that's the jury, of course—"I gave her one, they gave him two—" why, that must be what he did with the tarts, you know—

ALICE
But it goes on "They all returned from him to you."

KING OF HEARTS
(pointing triumphantly to the tarts)
Why, there they are! Nothing can be clearer than that. Then again—"Before she had this fit—" you never had fits, my dear, I think?

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Never!

She throws an inkstand at the LIZARD juryman BILL; ink trickles down his face; he writes with it on his slate.

KING OF HEARTS
Then the words don't fit you.
(smiles round the court; dead silence)
It's a pun!

Everybody laughs. The King looks offended, then recovers.

KING OF HEARTS
Let the jury consider their verdict.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
No, no! Sentence first—verdict afterwards.

ALICE
Stuff and nonsense! The idea of having the sentence first!

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(turning purple)
Hold your tongue!

ALICE
I won't!

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(at the top of her voice)
Off with her head!

Nobody moves. Alice has grown to her full size.

ALICE
Who cares for you? You're nothing but a pack of cards!

The whole pack rises into the air and comes flying down upon her. She gives a little scream—half fright, half anger—and tries to beat them off—

EXT. RIVERBANK - DAY

—and finds herself lying on the bank, her head in her Sister's lap. Sister gently brushes away dead leaves that have fluttered down from the trees upon her face.

SISTER
Wake up, Alice dear! Why, what a long sleep you've had!

ALICE
Oh, I've had such a curious dream!

Alice tells her, as well as she can remember, all the strange adventures. When she finishes, Sister kisses her.

SISTER
It was a curious dream, dear, certainly: but now run in to your tea; it's getting late.

Alice gets up and runs off toward the house, still thinking what a wonderful dream it had been.

EXT. RIVERBANK - SUNSET

Sister remains, leaning her head on her hand, watching the setting sun, thinking of little Alice and all her wonderful adventures—until she too begins dreaming after a fashion.

In the golden light the grass rustles: the White Rabbit hurries by; a frightened mouse splashes through a neighbouring pool; teacups rattle as the March Hare and the Hatter share their never-ending meal; the Queen's shrill voice orders guests to execution; a pig-baby sneezes; plates crash; a gryphon shrieks; a lizard's slate-pencil squeaks; guinea-pigs choke; the Mock Turtle sobs in the distance—all the creatures of the dream thronging the ordinary bank.

Sister sits with closed eyes, half believing herself in Wonderland—knowing she has but to open them and all would change to dull reality: grass in the wind, a pool among reeds, sheep-bells, a shepherd boy, the clamour of a farm-yard, cattle lowing far off.

At last she pictures Alice grown—a woman who keeps the simple and loving heart of childhood, gathering other little children, making their eyes bright with many a strange tale, perhaps even with the dream of Wonderland of long ago—feeling their simple sorrows, finding pleasure in their simple joys, remembering her own child-life, and the happy summer days.

FADE OUT.

THE END
